\pard\f0\fs28   {\b 55. L. graecum} (Poiret) Rech. fil., {\i Denkschr. Akad. Wiss. Math.-Nat. Kl.} ({\i Wien}) {\b 105}({\b 1}): 427 (1943). Plant 10-35 cm, glabrous, usually rough. Leaves 20-40 × 4-12 mm, linear-lanceolate to obovate-spathulate, 1-veined, usually on long woody basal branches. Inflorescence usually with numerous non-flowering branches; segments 1-2 cm, more than 0·7 mm in diameter; scales 3-4 mm. Spikes 3-5(-8) cm, with 1-3 spikelets per cm; spikelets 1- to 5-flowered, straight, cylindrical. Inner bract 5·5-6(-8) mm, obtuse, rounded dorsally, usually tuberculate, with reddish-brown margin, sometimes hyaline near apex, dark when dry, forming a wide, subpatent envelope around the flowers; outer bract 1·5-2·5(-3) mm, overlapping 1/6-1/3 of the inner. Calyx 6-7 mm, narrowly conical after pollination; tube straight; limb 2/3 as long as the tube. Corolla 7-8 mm.{\i  Maritime rocks and sands. Mediterranean region, mainly in the islands}. Bl Co Cr Gr Sa Si. ({\i W. Asia}.)
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  ({\b a}) Subsp.{\b  graecum} ({\i Statice graeca} Poiret, {\i S. sieberi} Boiss.,{\i  S. hyssopifolia} Girard): Inflorescence-branches mostly diverging at not more than 45°. Leaves green in summer; sometimes with clusters of reduced leaves on the lower branches.{\i  S. Greece, S. Aegean region}.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28   A very variable subspecies, containing two widespread variants having linear-spathulate and obovate-spathulate leaves respectively, and differing in the arrangement of the leaves and the number of flowers per spikelet. Further study is required to clarify their status. Plants intermediate between {\b 55} and {\b 29}, {\b 53} and {\b 56} occur frequently.
\par

\pard\f0\fs28   ({\b b}) Subsp.{\b  divaricatum} (Rouy) Pignatti,{\i  Bot. Jour. Linn. Soc.}{\b  64:} 366 (1971) ({\i Statice virgata }var.{\i  divaricata} Rouy): Inflorescence branches diverging at an angle of (45°-)60°-90°(-120°). Leaves usually withered in summer; cauline leaves absent.{\i  Islands of W. & C. Mediterranean region}.
\par

